**Describe the bug**
Version 3.3.1.
The animation from `setAnimation(...)` sometimes does not start. 

Here is my code upon click events:

    cancelAnimation()
    if (turnOn) {
        progress = 0f // I want the animation to restart from the beginning
        setAnimation(R.raw.lottie_turned_on)
        playAnimation()
    } else {
         setImageResource(R.drawable.ic_turned_off)
    }

After looking deeper into this, I believe there is a racing condition. Below is the flow I observed.

So in LottieAnimationView https://github.com/airbnb/lottie-android/blob/master/lottie/src/main/java/com/airbnb/lottie/LottieAnimationView.java, 

Inside the `setAnimation(resId)` method, it instantiates a `LottieTask` which executes a `LottieFutureTask` asynchronously to retrieve a cached composition. While this future task is executing to fetch a `result`, `setAnimation(resId)` proceeds to call `setCompositionTask(task);`. This method updates the reference of `this.compositionTask` to the new `task` after chaining a method call to `.addListener(loadedListener)`. 

In the `addListener(...)` method, it triggers a listener callback immediately if `result` already exists.

    if (result != null && result.getValue() != null) {
      listener.onResult(result.getValue());
    }

The `listener.onResult(...)` then triggers a method call to `setComposition(...)` which performs the rendering. Inside `setComposition(...)`, there is this condition that early-exits the method. 

    boolean isNewComposition = lottieDrawable.setComposition(composition);
    enableOrDisableHardwareLayer();
    if (getDrawable() == lottieDrawable && !isNewComposition) {
      // We can avoid re-setting the drawable, and invalidating the view, since the composition
      // hasn't changed.
      return;
    }

Lastly, `setComposition(...)` method leads to `onVisibilityChanged(...)` to start/resume the animation if it's ready to.

Here is the problem. 
If the future task completes before the `addListener(...)` method is called, the `if (result != null && result.getValue() != null)` condition becomes true and immediately triggers `setComposition(...)` which is supposed to lead to rendering the animation, but it won't yet because the conditions in `onVisibilityChanged(...)` won't resume the animation. Then when the second (the expected one) call to `setComposition(...)` gets called, it will just early-exit the method because the `composition` has already been set from last time even though it didn't resume the animation.

Any ideas?

